Now, let the reply to the fourth argument be that a written dis· course is not the worked over one to which the law objects in the case of witnesses. Objection is made to that discourse which has been composed by several witnesses so that all ol them may seem to 133 be in harmony and speaking the truth. Consequently, the law does not speak at all ol one witness, but ol several witnesses: “ Whether they have submitted one and the same prepared statement.” A prepared statement of another sort would not be objected to.
